{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f8fe1e90-057a-4746-b6d2-2a0a961d5085","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory, so here's general guidance on switching to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### What to change in your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**1. Add `id-token: write` permission** so the runner can request an OIDC token:\n\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # required for trusted publishing\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**2. Replace `dotnet nuget push` with the OIDC flow:**\n\n```yaml\n- name: Push to NuGet\n  run: dotnet nuget push \"**/*.nupkg\" --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n  # No --api-key needed!\n```\n\n**3. Remove** any references to `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY`.\n\n### What to configure on nuget.org\n\n1. Go to your package's **Manage → Trusted Publishers** page on nuget.org.\n2. Add a **GitHub Actions** trusted publisher entry with:\n   - **Repository owner** – your GitHub org/user\n   - **Repository name** – the repo name\n   - **Workflow filename** – e.g. `publish.yml`\n   - **(Optional)** Environment name, if you use a GitHub environment\n\n### Key points\n- The OIDC token is scoped to the specific repo + workflow, so no long-lived secret is needed.\n- If you use a GitHub **environment** (e.g. `production`), specify it both in the workflow (`environment: production`) and in the nuget.org trusted publisher config.\n- You can delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret from your repo settings once verified.\n\nWould you like me to create a sample workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6c251dd9-e8b3-47b8-a822-71fbbd788d43","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory appears to be empty. The user is asking a general question about switching from NuGet API key to trusted publishing (OIDC). Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":459,"requestId":"C817:2AF1D1:A1D7E:CCEFA:69F54B22"},"id":"795c1fca-2052-4706-91e4-a4bddac61149","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:54:06.546Z","parentId"